Schinopsis brasiliensis Engl.
is a plant belonging to the Anacardiaceae family, known as “baraúna”, “bŕauna” or “quebracho”, and characterized by arboreal habitat, with dimensions close to 15 m high. It can be found in the Brazilian semi-arid regions and it is a native species of the Caatinga and Atlantic forest (
). This plant is considered by the “First National Report for the Convention on Biological Diversity” (CBD) as an endangered species, due to the extensive utilisation of its wood in general construction (
).

Different parts of 

S. brasiliensis

, including leaves, fruits, and mainly bark are used in Brazilian traditional medicine for the treatment of various diseases, such as inflammation, influenza, cough, diarrhea, dysentery, and as vermifuge (

; 

). 

S. brasiliensis

has also been used as a natural antiseptic to treat wounds and superficial mycoses (

).

Previous phytochemical investigations on 

S. brasiliensis

leaves reported the presence of tannins and polyphenols, such as methyl gallate, gallic acid, ellagic acid derivatives (

), and flavonoids (

). Phytochemical investigation of the MeOH extract of 

S. brasiliensis

stems showed the presence of a biflavonoid and a chalcone (

), while from 

S. brasiliensis

bark an alkyl phenol along with a steroid derivative were isolated (

).

In order to unambiguously elucidate their structures by NMR experiments, the ethanol extract was purified by size exclusion chromatography, followed by further purification steps by reversed-phase HPLC-RI, to obtain sixteen compounds. Their structures were established by 1D and 2D-NMR experiments along with ESIMS and HRESIMS analysis (
Fig. 2
).

